âœ… What are Non-Alphanumeric Characters?

Alphanumeric characters =
            ðŸ‘‰ Letters (Aâ€“Z, aâ€“z) + Digits (0â€“9)

So, non-alphanumeric characters are:

            Symbols: @, #, $, %, &, *, etc.

            Punctuation: ., ,, !, ?, :, etc.

            Whitespace: space, tab, newline

            Special chars: ^, ~, ', ", /, \, etc.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------


âœ… How to check for non-alphanumeric in Java?

ðŸ”¸ 1. Using Character class

char ch = '@';

if (!Character.isLetterOrDigit(ch)) {
    System.out.println("Non-alphanumeric character");
} else {
    System.out.println("Alphanumeric character");
}

    Character.isLetterOrDigit(char) â†’ âœ… returns true for a-z, A-Z, 0â€“9

    We used ! to check non-alphanumeric


ðŸ”¸ 2. Using Regular Expressions (for Strings)

Check if a string contains any non-alphanumeric characters:

    String str = "Hello@123";

    if (str.matches(".*[^a-zA-Z0-9].*")) {
        System.out.println("Contains non-alphanumeric characters");
    } else {
        System.out.println("Only alphanumeric characters");
    }


Regex explained:

    [^a-zA-Z0-9] â†’ means not a letter or digit

    .*...* â†’ allows matching anywhere in the string
